 cost drivers, calculating absorption rates, calculating total overhead costs, and calculating overhead cost per unit.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF ACTIVITY-BASED COST\":\"This example illustrates how a company assembles two product models, Basic and Deluxe, and calculates the overhead costs using activity-based costing. It includes steps for identifying cost drivers, calculating cost per unit of cost drivers, and determining total overhead costs for each product.\"", "\"COST DRIVERS\":Cost drivers are factors that cause the cost of an activity to increase or decrease. Examples of cost drivers include machine setup costs, machine running costs, procurement costs, and delivery costs.", "\"TOTAL OVERHEAD COST\":\"Total overhead cost is the sum of all indirect costs associated with the production of goods. This includes costs such as utilities, rent, and administrative expenses.\"", "\"ABSORPTION RATE\":\"Absorption rate is calculated by dividing the total overhead cost by the total number of units of the cost driver. For example, Absorption rate = Total overhead cost / Total number of machine hours.\"", "\"INDIRECT COSTS\":\"Indirect costs\" are expenses that are not directly tied to a specific product or activity and cannot be directly traced to a specific cost object. Examples of indirect costs include utilities, rent, and administrative salaries. These costs are often allocated to different departments or products.", "\"DIRECT COSTS\":\"DIRECT COSTS\" are expenses that can be directly traced to a specific cost object, such as a product, department, or activity. Examples of direct costs include raw materials and direct labor.", "\"COST ALLOCATION\":\"Cost allocation is the process of assigning indirect costs to different cost objects, such as products, departments, or projects.\"", "\"COST OBJECT\":A cost object is any item for which a separate measurement of cost is desired. Examples of cost objects include products, services, departments, and projects.", "\"BATCH SET-UPS\":\"Batch set-ups refer to the preparation activities required to start a new production batch. This can include cleaning equipment, changing tools, and setting up machines.\"", "\"DISPATCH ORDERS\":\"Dispatch orders are instructions to send goods to a specific destination. They are often used in logistics and supply chain management.\"", "\"INSPECTIONS\":\"Inspections involve examining products or processes to ensure they meet specified standards and requirements.\"", "\"ABC APPROACH\":\"Activity-Based Costing (ABC) approach allocates overhead costs based on multiple cost drivers, reflecting the actual effort and cost incurred in producing small batches. This approach results in a higher cost per unit for products like the Deluxe model, which should have a higher selling price to justify the higher costs incurred.\"", "\"QUIZ: ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING V ABSORPTION COSTING\":\"This quiz compares the total cost for each product using traditional absorption costing and the ABC system. It involves calculating the cost per unit for products A and B under both costing methods and identifying the main reasons for the differences.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}